#6 Emergence of talent ‚Äì when confronted with crises, people rise to the challenge and rally around projects or solutions that they can contribute to in order to better their world. ‚úä

#5 Dramatic policy shifts ‚Äì crises can motivate the public to demand change or force leaders to make significant changes that, before the crisis, could have required immense courage or led to political suicide. üèõ
#4 Systemic change ‚Äì crises can overturn old norms and overcome resistance of the existing power structures to change, sometimes even by destroying those structures and practices. ü§Ø

#3 New levels of cooperation‚Äîeven among rivals ‚Äì problems that are bigger than individual interests of organizations or nations can necessitate cooperation and closer relationships, while opening an opportunity for more in the future. ü§ù
#2 Increased resiliency for the next event ‚Äì the impact of the disruption, and the innovation it led to can galvanize support to prepare for the next crisis. üèó
#1 Rapid problem solving and innovation ‚Äì a crisis can motivate innovative responses to what is seen as a clear and present danger. üí≠
After an extensive review of historical analysis, The Brookings Institution found that crises continually bring unexpected benefits in the following ways:

This, along with new ways of combining these new technologies, paves the way for scale-up that makes the new products and services more affordable and viable. This creates new opportunities and even more innovations that play their part in catalyzing new growth.

Researchers found waves of innovation that seem to come in patternsüåä üåä Often a crisis occurs, innovation happens in response, then a society grows out of the crisis, and new technologies find a more robust markets with new applications and uses for the technology.

They found that the two largest causes of innovation by far are problem-driven and technological opportunities. These could catalyze 2-4X the amount of innovation that comes from institutionalized search or market opportunities.

A Swedish study looked at 3,377 cases of innovation. üá∏üá™ They broke the innovation triggers into four categories:1. Market opportunities 2. Institutionalized search (paid innovation)3. New technological opportunity4. Problem-driven solutions (response to a crisis)

When we have faced crises in the past, we have responded in many cases with new innovations and adaptations that helped us survive, and even made us more successful. But how does this happen and what is the relationship between crisis, #innovation, and growth? üöÄ

Now the script and all the recordings go to our producer Dave Lishansky. Dave digs through our mountains of audio and gives us the ‚Äúvox cut‚Äù‚Äîjust voices, no music or sound effects.
We fix our little (and sometimes not-so-little) mistakes, and it‚Äôs time for Laur to record her narration.

Draft 2 (eventually, after much discussion) looks good. So we sent it to our fact checker. This is really important to us: we reach a big audience, we‚Äôre providing an important service in explaining climate change, and we want to get everything right.

Instead, we decided to zero in on the farm. How will farmers experience climate change in different parts of the world? And how do farmers‚Äô decisions affect the course of climate change? On to draft 2!

Our second hard choice: we weren‚Äôt going to talk (much) about individual foods. We wanted to get into how climate change might‚Äîwe stress MIGHT‚Äîaffect what‚Äôs on our plates in the future. But some things just have to go.
It‚Äôs a great concept that gets to the heart of why we care about climate change and food. And we couldn‚Äôt thoroughly explain it in less than 4 minutes. A third of our whole episode!

For this episode, we made two hard choices. First, we did away with our whole framing device. We wanted to organize the episode around four principles of food security Cynthia outlined: is food available? Affordable? Nutritious? And do we have a reliable supply?

Read more on the world's plausible pathways to net zero in our 2022 New Energy Outlook. https://t.co/4tTvTKMWso #BNEFNEO

In our Net Zero Scenario, oil, gas and coal consumption all peak nearly immediately, if they have not done so already. Under this scenario global coal demand peaks in 2022, gas demand peaked in 2021, and oil demand peaked in 2019, before the Covid-19 pandemic. https://t.co/YbUZyNNzbg

Switching power generation from fossil fuels to clean power is the single biggest contributor to global emission reductions in our Net Zero Scenario, accounting for half of all emissions abated over 2022-50. https://t.co/Mp3FpFYZEx

Our modelling shows that, while a pathway that limits global temperature increases to 1.5 ¬∞C by 2050 looks out of reach, there are still pathways to stay within 1.77C of warming in our Net Zero Scenario. Emissions need to fall by 30% by 2030 and overall 6% a year to 2040. https://t.co/GZncFbNh9m

Global power sector emissions have most likely peaked in 2022. To stay on track for net-zero, emissions in all sectors need to peak now and start declining. In our Net Zero Scenario, transport sector emissions peak in 2024 and fall quickly due to electric vehicles. https://t.co/g6huAZesmj

Keynote 1 by Kristie L. Ebi on Climate change and health to end this first day https://t.co/KivjC5Hl1a

End of session 2Thanks to all speakers ! ü§©Moreover, thanks a lot to all the organisers @RmnHoffmann Raya Muttarak @shonali_p Jonas Peisker @estriess and Andrea Tamburini. And of course, a lot of thanks for the whole @WiCVienna team üòç

Fourth talk by @tmshajdu on climate change and pregnancy lossesKey take-away: In Hungary, each day over 25¬∞C increases the weekly pregnancy loss rate by 1.4%. Under SSP2-4.5, the pregnancy loss rate is expected to increase by 1.1% in the 2090s, for SSP5-8.5 it increases by 2.2%

Third talk by Diego Ramiro-Fari√±as on the burden of heat-treated mortality in Madrid over 130 yearsKey take-away: The analysis shares the conclusion of the previous talk. Over a longer time span, the reduction in the cold temperature related risk is even more striking.

Relative-risk of cold temperatures are longer lasting than hot temperatures that have short term effects. Moreover the effects of cold temperatures declined over time whereas hot temperatures effects remained more or less stable before a small decline after 2009

Second talk by @dordanovich on temporal variation of the temperature-mortality association in SpainKey take-away: the relative-risk overall cumulative association of mortality with temperature is U-shaped.
People living in cities with more than 500.00 inhabitants are shown to be more vulnerable which partially confirm an heat island effects on mortality.

First talk by Mikhail Maximenko on the spatial patterns of excess mortality related to the 2010 heatwave in European RussiaKey take-away: the 2010 heatwave would be responsible of 57.700 [41.700 - 72.400] excess death in European Russia.
Now let's get back to work!Beginning of session chaired by @ConteRisto and Andrea Tamburini on Climate change and mortality
A well-deserved coffe break ! https://t.co/nG7Sl4dvAR
End of session 1 ! Thanks a lot to all speakers ü•≥ü•≥

Fourth talk by @beth_fussell on Disaster impacts on health and demographic outcomesKey take-away: A case studies approach is often used in disaster studies whereas experiment designs should be preferred with the use of pre-exposition data and the definition of a control group

Third talk by @J_D_Klein Climate change and health transition in AntananarivoKey take-away: Antananarivo has undergone a remarkable epidemiological transition. However, it is vulnerable to counter health transition from re-emerging enteric infections

Second talk by @francemente on Extreme Heat and Health in Old AgeKey take-away: Effects of the number of days above 30¬∞C on elderly are heterogeneous by SES. High SES people face less risk of hospitalisation than Low and Middle SES ones. It could be due to different vulnerabiliy

First talk by Liliana Andriano on the Effects of heatwave on birth weight in sub-Saharan AfricaKey take away: Infants exposed to heatwave during the second trimester of gestation have significant lower birthweights due to reduced gestational age at birth
Beginning of session 1 on Climate Change and Wellbeing chaired by @Sonja_Spitzer and @goujon_anne
